This paper compared sit-and-wait lizards (M.suborbitalis and P.lineoocellata) and wide-foraging lizards (H.lugubris and P.namaquensis), Table 1 includes raw data and size-corrected means + 1SE, no info on sex as morphological measurements were taken froMmusueMspecimens, therefore biteforce and morphometric data are froMdifferent sample sizes (see table 1).

In this paper there was data on jaw length (JL) which the methods state was the anterior tip oFthe lower jaw to posterior tip oFthe retroarticular process. Since this description confirms that this measurement was for the lower jaw, then I believe it is synonymous to other papers measurement oFlower-jaw length (LJL). This paper has different sample sizes for morphometric and bite force data. Morphometric data was taken froMmusueMspecimens and bite force data was taken froMindividuals in the field (SVL and BMdata was also collected too). It doesn't state but I assume the average morph and bFdata is across both sample sizes and that data collected in the field was froMadults? No data given on sex.

No information is provided on age or sex of taxa, analyses and results are presented only on the species as a whole. UPDATE: Natalie has confirmed they are likely to be adults due to SVL and BF values.
This paper looked at how BF performance predicts dominance in male venerable collared lizards. BF was the only significantly different trait between winners and losers.

This paper had two variables for head width (HW-t and HW-am). Hw-t was head width at the quadrate articular jaw joints (shorter than Hw-am). Hw-aMwas headwidth at the maximuMlateral extent oFthe temporal jaw-adductor musculature. Since Hw-aM was the maximum head width, these values were used for head width data. Head depth data was also available from this paper and used as proxy for head height.

This was an interesting paper, the authors captured the lizards and marked them, they then tried to recapture the same lizards to see iFthey "survived", the data was split into survivors/non-survivors and breeding season/non breeding season. The morphometric and BFvalues I used were oFthe survivor males (n = 12) and survivor females (n = 9) from Table 1. This is because these lizards were recaptured and remeasured, whereas the non-survivor lizard data was from lizards that were not recaptured and presumed dead. the MAX BF for males and females is very close too (0.02 for females) and so wouldn't have mattered too much.

This paper had different sample sizes for SVL (M= 39, F= 47) and BF, HL, HW, HH (M= 9, F= 10). They captured this species and recorded SVL and head measurements, however the BFand head measurement data used in the paper was froMthe same individuals captured in 1998 (with the smaller sample size)

This paper compared an ancestral population (Pod Kopiste)  oFPodarcis sicula with an introduced population (Pod Mrcaru), looking at how morphology, perfomance (BF), diet analysis and overall abudance had changed after 36 years. The sample sizes for morphometric and BFare divided into the two populations (no division based on sex, see methods for sample sizes). The data I've input froMthis paper is from the Pod Mrcaru population, i.e. the introduced island population as it had a higher max bf of 11.25 vs 9.85 for the ancestral population. The sample sizes were provided but for the whole population (SSM = 158, SSBF = 58) not for females and males seperately therefore no data available for sample sizes. BAD = no sample sizes for males and females

Taxa was named L.ceii in the paper, upon searching for diet and habitat data in Mieris paper, I could not find any taxa named L.ceii, Reptile databased revealed that it had been redescribed as Liolaemus kriegi â€” TRONCOSO-PALACIOS et al. 2014. Made a note but stuck to name as described in paper (L.ceii).

Taxa was named L.zullyi in the paper, upon searching for diet and habitat data in Mieris paper, I could not find any taxa named L.zullyi, Reptile databased revealed that it had been redescribed as Liolaemus zullyae â€” MIchels and Bauer, 2004 and there was a row for L.zullyae in Meiris database. Made a note but stuck to name as described in paper (L.zullyi).

This paper looked at males during the breeding season (n = 110 - 112) and post-breeding season (n = 33), no data for females. Sample size for morphometrics was 110- 112, sample size for bite force was 112. Breeding season data was used as it had a much larger sample size and because it had the higher max BF for the species. When trying to find habitat and diet data in Mieri DB, I discovered this taxa was renamed Aspidoscelis sexlineatus â€” PYRON & BURBRINK 2013.

This paper compared biteforce and head shape in a specialised durophagous (ability to eat hard-shelled prey) with a closely related species. Morph and BFdata was provided for both adults and juveniles for both species.  Data was taken from adults, no data was provided RE sex.

Taxa was named T.merianae in the paper, upon searching for diet and habitat data in Mieris paper, I could not find any taxa named T.merianae, Reptile databased revealed that it had been redescribed as Salvator merianae â€” HARVEY et al. 2012 and there was a row for S.merianae in Meiris database. It was renamed Tupinambis merianae â€” CROTHER et al. 2017. Made a note but stuck to name as described in paper (T.merianae).

This paper looked at interspecific interactions between males and females oFtwo different species oFanoles. They tested whether species ID, biteforce, dewlap size and body size affected the outcome oFdominance interactions between the two taxa. Data was only for average SVL (SE) and BF(SE), no data on head morph. Also already collected data for A.carolinesis.

This paper looked at whether dietary niche breathe is linked to morphology and performance in Nucras lizards. They established a phylogeny for this genus using mtDNA and nuclear markers and identified clusters. They collected dietary data on 5 Nucras spcies and using geometric morphometrics to analyse cranial shape and see iFthis was correlated withd dietary data. Sample sizes were different for morphometric and BFdata. Sexes were combined for the dietary analysis as it was assumed there were no significant differences in prey between sexes, therefore no data was available for sex (I believe taken froMVan De Meer, 2011). Morph measurements were taken froMmusueMspecimens, BFdata taken in vivo. REMOVE!

This paper looked at how sexual dimorphisMmay affect bite force within the Chameleon B.melanocephalum/B.thambobates species complex. As well as these two species, there were 3 other phenotypic forms (Type A, B and C). I only included data on the described B.melanocephalum/B.thamnobates as they are officially recognised taxa.

This was a typical paper looking at how morphology, ecology and biteforce are interrelated between two closely related taxa. Both taxa are rock-dwelling cordylid lizards. THIS PAPER WAS MISSING FROMVOLBIFDB

Sagonas et al. 2014 has data for Lacerta trilineata, both mainland (Eprirus, Thessalia, Peloponnese) and island (Crete, Andros, Skyros) taxa. Sample size for mainland (M= 13, F= 12) is similar to island (M=12, F=12). I used data from the island population as it had a higher max BF for both males and females. Paper not in VolBiFDB.

This paper looked at sex differences in BFand how this correlates with morph measurements. The raw morph and BFdata was for 12 individual lizards (7 males, 5 females). I averaged theMmyselFand calculated the SD myself.

This paper looked at BFin tuataras, they measured BFat both the tips oFthe jaw and at the posterior oFthe jaw. I took BFvalues froMtips oFjaw recommended by Marc. No SD/SE as was only one male/one female. BAD = no SD or SE as sample size was 1

Segall, et al., 2013 (J Exp Biol) - this paper looks at the effect oFtemperature on biteforce in two species oFdwarFchameleon (B.pumiluMand B.occidentale).  There is data available for mean mass and SVL for both species, n = 10 for each species, paper states that one male and nine females were captured for each species, however mass and SVL is averaged across sex, therefore unable to obtain sex data. No data available for head morphometrics. There is data available for bite force, however bite force was collected at different temperatures (15-35 degrees celsius, in increments oF5 degrees). COLLECTED BFDATA FROM25 DEGREES CELSIUS AS THIS TEMP WITH MAX BFVALUE FOR BOTH SP - (NC) but worth noting in the discussion that BFvaries depending on lots oFecological parameters and that we have simplified the analysis

This paper looked at BFin Komodo Dragons, Morph data was available for ten captive indiv ( M= 6, F= 4). Results state that "A total oF200 bite force peaks were collected froM22 trials. Regressions indicate maximuMbite force correlates best with mass, but also well with TL (Figure 2). All monitors produced a wide range oFforces, but heavier monitors produced greater maximuMforces with the highest at 148.56 N. HL and HW show much less significant correlations with bite force." Therefore MAX BF= 148.56, morph data was taken from largest male in the sample (n=1) to match with BF data. This is slightly dodgy so important to note this may need revising.
Bad = no SD or SE with averages due to sample size of 1, can use in MAX BF analysis but not in analysis with SD or SE

This paper had morph (SVL and BM) data available for M, F and M+F. I decided to use overall data for M+F(M=10,F=11) as the BFdata was only available for M+F. This paper collected data on different thermal accliamation treatements between 20-34 degrees celsius, I inferred max BFdata froMFigure 4B which was pre thermal acclimation treatments as this had the highest BFfor the species. Using a ruler I calculated that 3cMon the graph = 5 newtons. Therefore 1cM= 1.666 N. I estimated that BFto be approximately 16.5N + 3.32 (2cMon the graph). This was at a body temperature oF20 degrees celsius. The BFdata had a slightly smaller sample size, 1 less male). "Ok data" - had to derive BF and SD from graph

This paper looked at P.muralis populations froMItaly and France. There was a higher max BFfor males froMthe Italian population, males and females froMFrance and females froMItaly had lower max BFthat recorded froMprevious studies so did not include data on them. Average morph and BFdata was available froMSupp info Table S1, however there was a slight discrepancy in avg BF, so I decided to calculate avg, sd and min and max using a link to the Dryad repository which contained raw morph and BFdata and indicated that max BFfor P.muralis males was 13.64 froMthe Italian population. This paper looked at sexual dimorphism in two populations of T.mauritanica. Female data was froMthe Palacio De Donana population, and male data was froMthe Matalascanas population as these had the max BFfor this species. Substrate category was inferred in text as well as sample sizes.

There was BFdata available for the two localities studied (North/South population), max BF was from the Southern males (n = 10, BF= 46.61 + 6.38), however there was no morph data available other than that the average SVL for the southern population was 95.17 (no SD or SE provided). I input max BFfor southern males, but could average across males and females to match up with SVL which is average for males and females. "Remove" - dodgy data
